1. Introduction

Dataset 1: Texas Health Rankings

The first data set was provided by the County Health Rankings & Roadmaps (CHR&R) program by University of Wisconsin Population Health Institute. The dataset was retrieved from https://www.countyhealthrankings.org/explore-health-rankings/texas/data-and-resources and covers various different health statistics, ranging from death and mortality (of both adults and infants), high school graduates, drinking accidents, etc.

The dataset contains 256 rows, where the first 2 rows are the column names and each other row in this dataset representing info about a particular county in Texas. In this dataset, there are 162 columns. Since the dataset originated from a Microsoft Excel sheet and was later converted to a CSV file, certain columns were merged and then un-merged without a proper name. Excluding these columns with missing names, there are 82 columns, which give a statistic to each County based on

  • Commute (Long commute - driving alone, ),

  • Housing (Driving alone to work, ),

  • Environmental Violations (Drinking water violations, Air pollution - particulate matter, ),

  • Crime, death, and injuries (Violent crime, Injury deaths, ),

  • and other Health Factors (Physical inactivity, Poor or fair health, Excessive drinking,).

What intrigued us about this data set was the possibility of health disparities between counties in Texas, and to see if perhaps wealthier counties had better health statuses than less-wealthy counties.

Dataset 2: Texas Commission on Environmental Quality

Our second dataset was provided by the Texas Commission on Environmental Quality. The dataset was retrieved from https://data.texas.gov/dataset/Texas-Commission-on-Environmental-Quality-Notices-/mwzi-gyw7 and covers investigations leading to a Notice of Violation (NOV).

The dataset contains 1.2 million rows, as it covers data from each county from 2011 to 2023. Each row in this dataset represents a Notice of Violation. In this dataset, there are 25 columns, correlating to

  • Identification (Customer Name, Investigation Number, Notice of Violation Date, ),

  • Location data (Mailing Address, County, Latitude, Longitude),

  • and Violation Classification (Rule Citation, Media, Violation Category).

What is particularly interesting about this dataset is while it does contain a plethora of environmental violations, there does not appear to be a grand number of classifications. For example, all of the information on NOVs seem to fall under only 3 media: Water, Air, and Waste. Similarly, NOVs fall under only 3 Violation Categories: A, B, and C.

Dataset 3 : Texas State Expenditures

Our third dataset was provided by the Texas Comptroller of Public Accounts. The dataset was retrieved from https://data.texas.gov/Government-and-Taxes/Texas-State-Expenditures-by-County-2018/f2iw-dtqt and documents the amounts of money allocated by the state of Texas to each county, as well as the corresponding expenditure category.

The dataset contains 88,707 rows, with each row representing a distinct expenditure made. The dataset contains 6 different variables, which are both

  • Numerical (Fiscal Year, Agency Number, and Amount),

  • and Categorical (Agency Name, County, and Major Spending Category).

What intrigued us about this data set was to see the relationship between the amount and category of money allocated. Furthermore, when investigating the top-ranked average salary group, we wondered if the counties represented would be well-known, larger counties.

RQ 1: Air Violations and Air Pollution

The first research question, that will be explored, is the relationship between the amount of air violations in a given county (in the dataset TX_Envm) and the average daily \(pm_{2.5}\) (in the dataset TX_Health).

Knowing this, lets create a joined dataset, RQ_1, for this research question utilizing both TX_Envm and TX_Health. However, we must keep some issues in mind:

  1. Both datasets will be joined by county. However, TX_Health has the counties capitalized in sentence case, while TX_Envm has the counties in upper case. This must be adjusted to allow for a proper join.
  2. The TX_Health dataset only has information from 2017, while TX_Envm contains data from many years. Therefore we must filter TX_Envm to contain data only from 2017. Making it more complicated however, the TX_Envm data has its dates listed in a mm/dd/yyyy format and will have to be split to into separate columns to be properly filtered.
  3. The TX_Health dataset has n/a values for county, symbolizing the total values for Texas. Therefore, these n/a values must be removed.
  4. Both datasets contain a lot of extraneous information that will not be used in this study, thus it will have to be filtered out. Specifics on the comparison between both datasets:
    • Share only 2 IDs: County and State (with all state values being Texas)
    • Do not share 104 separate IDs, with 23 different IDs in TX_Envm and 80 different IDs in TX_Health
    • In total, there will be 101 IDs that will be left out of this portion of the study.
  5. The column name Average Daily PM2.5 is clumsy, and will be changed to Pollution.

Cleaning Data:

## First Issue:
  TX_E<-TX_Envm # Convert dataset to a different name
  TX_E$County = str_to_sentence(TX_E$County) # Corrects the letter case for county column
  full_join(TX_Health, TX_E, by = "County") %>%  # Information from both datasets, join by county
## Second Issue: 
  separate(`Notice of Violation Date`, # Separates the date into 3 columns
           into = c("Month", "Day", "Year"),  # Columns: month, day, and year
           sep = "/",  
           convert = T) %>%
  filter(Year == '2017') %>% # Filters and leaves only data from 2017
## Third Issue: 
  filter(!is.na(County)) %>% # Filters and removes all n/a values for county
## Fourth Issue: 
  select(County, Media, "Violation Category","Average Daily PM2.5") %>% # Selects the columns
## Fifth Issue:
  rename(Pollution = 'Average Daily PM2.5' # Rename column into "Pollution"
          ) -> RQ_1 # Rename the new dataset to "RQ_1"

However, upon a quick glance at the dataset, one would notice many different variables without clear definitions. Therefore, a quick discussion about the semantics of key variables within our new dataset:

  • \(pm_{2.5}\): Withing the category Pollution, the unit \(pm_{2.5}\) describes the fine inhalable particles, with a diameter that are 2.5 micrometers or smaller (hence the name). It should be noted, that the World Health Organization (WHO) sets a standard of \(5 g/m^3\) (daily average) and the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) sets a standard of \(12 g/m^3\) (daily average). It is not our place to dictate which is correct, that distinction will be left for governmental agencies. However, it is a generally accepted that a larger number is associated with worse pollution, and will thus be interpreted in this manner.

  • Media: The Texas Commission on Environmental Quality (TCEQ) separates violations into three distinct categories: Air, Waste, and Water. Each category contains a broad range of violations, but all pertain to the category in which they are under. In this portion of the study, we will be investigating violations under the category of Air.

  • Violation Category: The Texas Commission on Environmental Quality (TCEQ) further separates violations based upon their Enforcement Initiation Criteria (EIC). This criteria assesses the severity of the violation and labels the violation either as A, B, or C:

    • A = A regulatory violation, it is the least severe and it typically manifests itself as a failure to report requirements (improper permits, failure to keep proper records, etc)

    • B = A general violation, it is not serious by nature but poses occupational health hazards to employees.

    • C = A serious violation, it is the most severe and poses serious health risks to the general public as well as employees.

Next, let us answer our research question: is there a relationship between number of air violations and air pollution in a county? Let us construct a bivariate visualization of the data.

## This function produces a bivariate graph of the total number of violations and respective air pollution for each county in Texas
RQ_1 %>%
  group_by(County) %>% # Groups all the data by county
  summarize(Total = n(), Pollution) %>%  # Count the total number of violations
  slice(1:1) %>% # Takes on observation of each county, with the new total variable

    ggplot(aes(x = Total, y = Pollution)) + # ggplot: total on the x-axis and pollution on the y-axis
    geom_point(aes(color=County)) +
    # Sets the title, caption, and x.y axis for the graph
    labs(title = "Relationship Between Total Air Violations and Air Pollution",
       caption = "Figure 2",
       x = "Total Air Violations",
       y = "Average Daily PM^2.5 (g/m^3)") +
  theme_light() +  # Sets the theme for the graph
  theme(legend.position = "none") + # Removes the legend
  scale_x_continuous(trans = 'log2') + # Sets the x-axis in the log scale
  geom_smooth(method = lm) #line of best fit for the data in the graph

The resulting graph displays the total number of violations against the average daily \(pm_{2.5}\) for each county, with \(pm_{2.5}\) having the units of \(g/m^3\). In addition, each point on the graph represents a separate county and is positioned based on the aforementioned characteristics. With the addition of a best fit line, it is incredibly apparent that there is a positive correlation between the total number of violations and the average daily \(pm_{2.5}\) within each county. It should be noted, however, that a decision was reached to set the x-axis at an exponential scale to properly suite the wide range of values. Nonetheless, this decision does not impact the conclusions made. In summary, there is a positive relationship between air quality and total number of air violations within counties in Texas.

RQ 2: Salaries/Wages Per County and Respective Health

In order to begin the exploration into the relationship between the amount of money for salaries and wages allocated to each county and the percentage of fair or poor health status, the data sets had to be cleaned in order to be properly joined. The expenditures data set was first filtered to only include data from the year 2017, and then only the rows with a county name were selected. The data was then filtered again to focus on the salaries and wages category, and then the rows were grouped by county. A summarize function was then used to calculate the total wages and salaries, as well as the average salaries and wages, each in units of thousands of dollars. By grouping by county, the new data set only included one row per county, which was the intended goal.

TX_2017_SalWage <- TX_Exp %>%
  filter(`Fiscal Year` == 2017) %>% # filtering expenditure data for only 2017 
  filter(!is.na(County)) %>% # Removing rows with missing county name
  filter(`Major Spending Category` == 'SALARIES AND WAGES') %>%  # Choosing the spending category 
  select(County, `Major Spending Category`, Amount) %>% 
  group_by(County) %>% # Grouping the data based on the county name
  # Total and average salaries will be in units of 1000s of dollars 
  summarize(Total_Sal_Wages = sum(Amount)/1000,
            Avg_Sal_Wages = mean(Amount)/1000)

nrow(TX_Exp)
## [1] 88707
nrow(TX_2017_SalWage)
## [1] 253

Next, the health data set was cleaned by removing rows with a missing county name, and by grouping the data by county as was done in the expenditures data set. The % Fair/Poor variable was then converted into a numeric variable, since it was originally classified as a character. The county names were then all capitalized in order to match the county name format in the expenditures data set, which would allow the two to be joined properly. The County variable was then used to join each data set, which resulted in a data set with 254 rows.

TX_HealthClean <- TX_Health %>%
  # Removing missing county observations 
  filter(!is.na(County)) %>%
  group_by(County) %>%
  # Mutating the character variable to now be a numeric variable 
  mutate(`% Fair/Poor` = as.numeric(`% Fair/Poor`), 
         # Capitalizing all county names in order to properly join with the other            # data set 
        County = toupper(County)) %>%
  select(County, `% Fair/Poor`)

# joining both datasets by the ID of 'County'
joinedHealthAndSal<-full_join(TX_2017_SalWage, TX_HealthClean, by = 'County')

RQ 3: Total Spending and Total Violations

We will be exploring the relationship between the expenditures made by each county in the dataset TX_Exp and the violations that occurred in the dataset TX_Envm_Violation.

It is important to first notice that TX_Exp and TX_Envm both contain information from several different years. For our investigation, we are interested in information during 2017. While we can filter this straight away with TX_Exp, we found that our TX_Envm dataset displays the dates in mm/dd/yyyy format. Thus, we separated the column into year, month, and day columns to allow us to filter out the years.

TX_2017_Exp <- TX_Exp %>%
  filter(`Fiscal Year` ==2017) # Look at only 2017 data

TX_2017_Envm <- TX_Envm %>%
  ## Tidying: Separating the column into 3 other columns ###
  separate(`Notice of Violation Date`, # We separate the date into 3 columns
           into = c("Month", "Day", "Year"),  # ...month, day, and year
           sep = "/",
           convert = T) %>%
  filter(Year == 2017) # ...then we filter 2017 data

Now, we want to calculate totals for both of the datasets before joining the two. We begin with calculating the total amount of expenditures performed by each county. Notice that our first county row is NA. A closer look at this row shows that this row looks at the totals of the entirety of Texas. Thus, for our data analysis, we would exclude this from our calculations.

TX_2017_TotalExp <- TX_2017_Exp %>%
  filter(!is.na(County)) %>% # Filter out the "Texas Total" row
  select(County, `Major Spending Category`, Amount) %>% # look at counties and amounts
  group_by(County) %>% # for each county...
  summarize(Total_Exp_HTh = sum(Amount)/100000, # ... Find the total expenditure
            Avg_Exp_HTh = mean(Amount)/100000) # .. Find the average expenditure

With this summarization, we can take a look at how spread out the expenditure amounts are among the counties:

summary(TX_2017_TotalExp$Total_Exp_HTh)

  • The average amount of total spending performed by a county is around $668 hundreds of thousands of dollars ($66,787,000).
  • 87 Counties are missing totals

Next, we do the same total calculations for our Texas Environment dataset.

TX_2017_TotalEnvm <- TX_2017_Envm %>%
  group_by(County) %>% # For each county...
  summarize("Total_Violations" = n()) # Count the # of violation

With totals calculated for each of our counties based on each dataset, we can now join the two datasets and graph the total expenditures against the total number of violations.

When joining, we notice that:

  • There are 250 observations in TX_2017_TotalEnvm and 254 observations in TX_2017_TotalExp.
  • The main ID variable used to join the two summary datasets is County.
  • The variables not shared by both datasets include the calculated Total_Violations, Total_Exp_Hth, and Avg_Exp_Hth.
  • For now, other variables originally present in our datasets, such as Media from TX_Envm and Major Spending Category from TX_Exp do not appear in our join.

After joining the datasets using inner_join, we found that we now have 250 observations, meaning there are 4 counties in TX_2017_TotalExp that were not included in our join: Collingsworth, Hansford, Hartley, and King county. Searching for these counties in the violations does not produce any results, meaning that these counties perhaps had either 0 violations during 2017 or violation data for these counties was not found. Because the populations of these counties, specifically King, are super low, excluding these counties would not influence our data significantly.

left_join(TX_2017_TotalEnvm, TX_2017_TotalExp, by = "County") %>%
  
  ggplot(aes(x = Total_Violations, y = Total_Exp_HTh)) +

The resulting graph shows the total number of violations against the total expenditure amount of each county, with expenditure amounts being in $100k amounts. With the addition of a best fit line, there does appear to be a positive trend between violation totals and expenditure totals. However, a major cluster of data is centered around low expenditure and low violation amounts. In addition to this cluster, certain counties ranked extremely high in total expenditure amounts despite having a low number of violations. It might be that the use of $100k amounts rather than $1 amounts influences the data to appear to have a positive correlation. While the line does suggest a positive trend, the scale of our y-axis emphasizes that a large amount of money would be needed to show any correlation between violation amounts.

Comparing the total violations and total expenditures on their own produces interesting results, but perhaps inclusion of the type of violation could demonstrate further relationships. We thus introduce the Media variable into our analysis.

3. Discussion

Through the methods in this study, three research questions were answered

Research Question 1: What is the relationship between the amount of air violations in a given county and the average daily \(pm_{2.5}\)?

  • Figure 1 displays the range of average daily \(pm_{2.5}\) for all counties in Texas, establishing that all counties in Texas have average daily \(pm_{2.5}\) emissions that are below the regulation as set by the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) of \(12 g/m^3\). In the same vein, Figure 2 provide a clear picture as to the relationship between the total amount of air violations and air pollution. Through visualization of the trend line, as seen it figure 2, there is a positive correlation between the total amount of air violations and average daily \(pm_{2.5}\).

Research Question 2: What is the relationship between the amount of money for salaries and wages allocated to each county and the respective percentage of fair or poor health status?

  • Figure 3 demonstrated that the counties in the top 10 ranks for salary and wage allocation from the state of Texas exhibited a relationship that was similar to what was hypothesized. That is, for an increase in the amount allocated for salaries and wages, the percentage of fair and/or poor health status among that countys population decreased. It is important to note that the correlation was not strong, but a visual inspection confirms that it is not 0, though for a more rigorous proof significance of correlation should be tested.
  • Figure 4 revealed that on a state-wide scale, the same pattern was not as apparent. However, it is important to note that not many observations were apparent past $6,000,000, meaning the regression line could be inaccurate.
  • Further analysis should investigate what confounding variables could be influencing health statuses.

Research Question 3: What is the relationship between the expenditures made by each county in Texas and their respective violations?

  • Figure 5 displays the number of violations against the total amount of expenditure made by each county. Each county was represented with a point and a line of best fit was added into the data. Certain outliers were removed from the finishing plot in order to focus on the cluster of data. From the cluster, we found that there does seem to be a positive correlation between Expenditure Totals and Violation Totals. However, it is important to emphasize that the scale of expenditures was in Hundreds of Thousands of Dollars, meaning that such a correlation is actually weaker than what is depicted.
  • Figure 7 does a similar depiction as Figure 5 with the addition of the media variable. With this, 3 more lines were constructed, demonstrating if looking at specific types of violations demonstrated a better correlation. While Air and Waste-related violations did not show a significant correlation, Water Violations seemed to show a positive relationship between number of Violations and the total expenditure made by a county. The same issues as figure 5 follow, mainly being the scale used to construct the plot.
  • Figure 6 simply shows how many types of violations were classified as being labeled as either a Water, Air, or Waste related violation. The resulting bar graph showed that Water violations were overwhelmingly higher compared to the other types of media. This might explain why water-related environmental violations had a better correlation between number of violations and expenditure totals in Figure 7.

Reflection

The process of constructing this project was time-intensive and laborious. The project itself is the amalgamation of late nights, long hours, and multiple corrections divided amongst the three group mates. However, the process itself was enjoyable and an opportunity to grow stronger in the development of a new coding language. The process of constructing the end-product presented many new complications, that were not directly addressed in class. Therefore, it took ingenuity and creativity to format and solve through certain aspects of the project. Moreover, it took communication skills to work on a project that did not allow for corrections/editing to be made simultaneously. To combat this issue, we saved and distributed a .rmd file many times, with each person editing their portion of the work as time went on. This arduous process eventually led to one final draft in a .rmd file. All in all, the process of creating this work was difficult and presented many issues. However, it was an opportunity for each of us to grow stronger in R and our interpersonal skills.
